The Database hsb2

The hsb2 database is taken from a national survey of high school seniors.

More details about the survey can be found here:

  • High School and Beyond - Wikipedia
  • High School and Beyond - NCES

The data files contains a subset of students randomly sampled from the full database.

Key details

  • Number of observations: 200 students
  • Number of variables: 12
Variable Name Type Details
female nominal (0/1)
race nominal ethnicity (1=hispanic 2=asian 3=african-american 4=white)
ses ordinal socioeconomic status (1=low 2=middle 3=high)
schtyp nominal type of school (1=public 2=private)
prog nominal type of program (1=general 2=academic)
read scale standardized reading score
write scale standardized writing score
math scale standardized math score
science scale standardized science score
socst scale standardized social studies score
hon nominal passed with honors in English (0/1)

Analysis steps:

  • Load the data into R
  • Check the contents of the loaded data
  • Convert the columns into labelled factor variables
  • Investigate:
    • reading score vs writing score
    • maths score by race
    • science score by socioeconomic status
    • passed with honors English vs type of school
  • Make a new column “english” containing the average of the reading and writing score
  • Make a new column “overall” containing the average of the all subject scores
  • Compare overall score between male and female students
  • Create a new data frame containing only public school students
  • Create a new data frame containing only the overall scores and socioeconomic status for public school students.

Convert the columns into labelled factor variables

highschool$race <- factor(highschool$race, 
                           levels = c(1,2,3,4),
                           labels = c("hispanic", 
                                      "asian", 
                                      "african-american", 
                                      "white") )

highschool$ses <- factor(highschool$ses, 
                           levels = c(1,2,3),
                           labels = c("low", 
                                      "middle", 
                                      "high") )

highschool$gender <- factor(highschool$female, 
                         levels = c(0,1),
                         labels = c("male", 
                                    "female") )

highschool$schtyp <- factor(highschool$schtyp, 
                            levels = c(1,2),
                            labels = c("public", 
                                       "private") )

remove column 2 which is female column

highschool <- highschool[ ,-2]

Investigate:

#  - reading score vs writing score
plot(highschool$read,highschool$write)

# plot using formula
plot(write~read, data=highschool)

# - maths score by race
plot(math~race, data=highschool)

# - science score by socioeconomic status
plot(science~ses,data=highschool)

# - race vs type of school
plot(race~schtyp, data=highschool)

# frquency table
table(highschool$race,highschool$schtyp)
                  
                   public private
  hispanic             22       2
  asian                10       1
  african-american     18       2
  white               118      27

Make a new column “english” containing the average of the reading and writing score Make a new column “overall” containing the average of the all subject scores

highschool$english <- (highschool$write + highschool$read)/2

Compare overall score between male and female students

highschool$overall <- (highschool$write +
                         highschool$read +
                         highschool$math +
                         highschool$science +
                         highschool$socst )/5

plot(overall~gender,data=highschool)

Create a new data frame containing only public school students

highschool_public <- subset(highschool, schtyp=="public")
highschool_public2 <- highschool[ which(highschool$schtyp=="public") , ]

Create a new data frame containing only the overall scores and socioeconomic status for public school students.

highschool_summary <- highschool[ , c('overall','ses')]

Exercise: Analysis of the children bodysize dataset

The file children_bodysize.csv contains body size measurements of children. Use the R commands we have covered to open and explore the dataset.

  • weight: mass in kg
  • stature: height in mm
  • head: head circumference in mm
  • shoulder: shoulder breadth in mm
  • hand_l: hand length
  • hand_w: hand width
  • waist: waist circumference
  • foot_l: foot length
  • foot_w: foot width
  • gender: gender
  • age: age (months)

Work in an R markdown file so that you can reproduce and share your work easily.

  1. Import the Tidyverse libraries

  2. Load the data into a data frame

  3. Check data types for each column

  4. Plot showing heights vs age

Answer the questions

  1. How many entries are in the dataset?

  2. What are the youngest and oldest ages of individuals in the dataset?

  3. What is the tallest individual in the dataset, are they male or female?

  4. How many boys are in the dataset?

  5. How many girls over the age of 12?

  6. What is the mean height of a 5 year old boy and 5 year old girl?

  7. What is the mean height of a 15 year old boy and 15 year old girl?

  8. Use a histogram to show the distribution of children’s ages

  9. What does the distribution of the heights of 9 year old males look like?

Challenges

  • Create a column height_cm containing the height in cm (1cm = 10mm)
  • Create a column containing the age in years
  • Plot showing the average height of children by age

plot(height ~ gender, 
     data = subset(bodysize, year_old==15 )

Plot height against age.

plot(height~age, data=bodysize, pch='.')

Using Tidyverse functions

If we need to convert a data frame to a tidyverse tibble we can use the tibble function:

# if we have a data.frame which is not already a tibble
# we can think of data frames and tibbles as being the same
# one difference is that tibbles don't have row names/labels
bodysize <- tibble(bodysize)

The select command

Select allows us to select columns from a data frame.

bodysize_modified <- select(bodysize, height, gender, age, year_old)

The group_by and summarise command

We can summarise information based on groups using the above commands.

bodysize_mod <- group_by(bodysize_mod, year_old)
height_by_age <- summarise(bodysize_mod, height = mean(height) )
plot(height~year_old, data=height_by_age, type="line")
Warning in plot.xy(xy, type, ...): plot type 'line' will be truncated to first
character

bodysize_mod <- group_by(bodysize_mod, year_old, gender)
height_by_age <- summarise(bodysize_mod, height = mean(height) )
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'year_old'. You can override using the
`.groups` argument.
plot(height~year_old, type="line", data=filter(height_by_age, gender=='M'))
Warning in plot.xy(xy, type, ...): plot type 'line' will be truncated to first
character
lines(height~year_old, col="red", data=filter(height_by_age, gender=='F'))
